{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}} {{Use British English|date=October 2016}} {{Infobox venue | name = Armadale Stadium | nickname = | image = | location = [[Armadale, West Lothian|Armadale]], [[West Lothian]] EH48 2PD | coordinates = | opened = 1939 | renovated = | expanded = | closed = | owner = | operator = | surface = | tenants = [[Edinburgh Monarchs|Edinburgh Monarchs speedway]] }}
'''Armadale Stadium''' is a [[motorcycle speedway]] and former [[greyhound racing]] stadium situated in the town of [[Armadale, West Lothian]] in Scotland. [[Stock car racing]] has also been held at the venue.
==Speedway== {{main article|Edinburgh Monarchs}} It has been home to the Edinburgh Monarchs speedway team since 1997.<ref>Bamford, R & Jarvis J.(2001). ''Homes of British Speedway''. {{ISBN|0-7524-2210-3}}</ref>
In 2009, the Edinburgh Monarchs reached agreement with [[Sainsbury's]] for the stadium to be purchased and re-developed as a supermarket, subject to planning permission being granted by [[West Lothian Council]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://news.stv.tv/east-central/176406-monarchs-in-new-stadium-hopes/ |title= Monarchs in new stadium hopes |date=2010-05-10 |access-date=2015-01-30}}</ref> This was not forthcoming, the application being rejected in June 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/motorsport/motorbikes/speedway/8673320.stm|title=Edinburgh Monarchs' Armadale switch rejected by council |date=2010-06-02|access-date=2015-01-30}}</ref>
==Greyhound racing== The greyhound track near Bathgate Road opened on 20 February 1939 just four days after the Armadale greyhound track at [[Volunteer Park, Armadale|Volunteer Park]] closed.<ref name=GS>{{cite web|url=http://greyhoundstar.co.uk/remember-february-8-2/|title=Remember When - February 1939|publisher=Greyhound Star}}</ref> In later years two races called the West Lothian Stakes and Armadale Sprint Championships were introduced and remained feature races. Track distances were 330 and 540 yards. <ref>{{cite book|last=Barnes|first=Julia|title=Daily Mirror Greyhound Fact File|page =270|year=1988|publisher=Ringpress Books|isbn=0-948955-15-5}}</ref> Armadale was mainly [[Handicapping|handicap races]] and there were regular opens for the higher class of greyhound with a main distance of 525 yards. TD Heffernan was involved in opening of the new track.<ref name=GS/>
The owners of Armadale greyhound stadium announced on 8 October 2016 that they were ending the greyhound operation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edinburghmonarchs.co.uk/news-centre/article/2016-10-08/stadium-clarification|title=Stadium clarification|publisher=Edinburgh Monarchs.co.uk}}</ref>
